05437nam a22008055i 9780812291117DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979756832  a97808122911177 a10.9783/97808122911172doi  a(DE-B1597)451288  a(OCoLC)905856024  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aF544b.M875 2015 7aHIS0360202bisacsh04a977.3/012231 aMorrissey, Robert Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEmpire by Collaboration :bIndians, Colonists, and Governments in Colonial Illinois Country /cRobert Michael Morrissey. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b24 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly American Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction. An Earnest Invitation -- tChapter 1. Opportunists in the Borderlands -- tChapter 2. The Imaginary Kingdom -- tChapter 3. Collaboration and Community -- tChapter 4. A Dangerous Settlement -- tChapter 5. Collaborators: Indians and Empire -- tChapter 6. Creolization and Collaboration -- tChapter 7. Strains on Collaboration in French Illinois -- tChapter 8. Demanding Collaboration in British Illinois -- tConclusion. The End of Collaboration -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the beginnings of colonial settlement in Illinois Country, the region was characterized by self-determination and collaboration that did not always align with imperial plans. The French in Quebec established a somewhat reluctant alliance with the Illinois Indians while Jesuits and fur traders planted defiant outposts in the Illinois River Valley beyond the Great Lakes. These autonomous early settlements were brought into the French empire only after the fact. As the colony grew, the authority that governed the region was often uncertain. Canada and Louisiana alternately claimed control over the Illinois throughout the eighteenth century. Later, British and Spanish authorities tried to divide the region along the Mississippi River. Yet Illinois settlers and Native people continued to welcome and partner with European governments, even if that meant playing the competing empires against one another in order to pursue local interests.Empire by Collaboration explores the remarkable community and distinctive creole culture of colonial Illinois Country, characterized by compromise and flexibility rather than domination and resistance. Drawing on extensive archival research, Robert Michael Morrissey demonstrates how Natives, officials, traders, farmers, religious leaders, and slaves constantly negotiated local and imperial priorities and worked purposefully together to achieve their goals. Their pragmatic intercultural collaboration gave rise to new economies, new forms of social life, and new forms of political engagement. Empire by Collaboration shows that this rugged outpost on the fringe of empire bears central importance to the evolution of early America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIndians of North AmericaxIllinoisxHistoryx17th century. 0aIndians of North AmericaxIllinoisxHistoryx18th century. 0aIndians of North AmericazIllinoisxHistoryy17th century. 0aIndians of North AmericazIllinoisxHistoryy18th century. 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aNative American Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2015z9783110438635o